            "body": {
              "mode": "raw",
              "raw": "{\n  \"text\": \"Formal verification is a technique used in computer science and engineering to prove or disprove the correctness of a system with respect to a certain formal specification or property, using formal methods of mathematics. It can be used to verify hardware and software systems. The verification of these systems is done by providing a formal proof on an abstract mathematical model of the system, and the correspondence between the mathematical model and the nature of the system is then done separately. Examples of mathematical objects often used to model systems are finite-state machines, labelled transition systems, Petri nets, vector addition systems, timed automata, hybrid automata, process algebra, formal semantics of programming languages such as operational semantics, denotational semantics, axiomatic semantics and Hoare logic.\"\n}",
              "options": {
                "raw": {
                  "language": "json"
                }
              }
            },
